  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a real, visceral experience I've felt firsthand. Growing up in Bologna with parents who only had vocational diplomas, I've always been aware of the 'math isn't for me' narrative that's so common among girls in my age group. When I take a math test, my mind races with the thought: 'What if they think I'm not good enough?' This anxiety isn't just about the test—it's about the broader belief that girls don't belong in STEM fields. As someone who's anxious and often feels like I'm not measuring up, stereotype threat hits me harder than most. I've seen how it affects my friends too—how they avoid challenging problems because they fear being judged. But here's the thing: we absolutely need to address this. In my small volunteer group that does community science outreach in Bologna, I've noticed that when we frame STEM as a journey of curiosity rather than a competition, students start to engage more deeply. Schools should integrate more inclusive language and mentorship programs that highlight diverse role models in STEM, not just the usual 'genius' stories. It's about creating safe spaces where students feel they belong, not just 'performing' well. For me, it's personal—my anxiety makes me hyper-aware of these threats, but it's also what drives me to advocate for change. If we don't tackle stereotype threat head-on, we're not just failing students; we're failing the future of innovation.",
